{{unreliable sources|date=August 2011}} {{Infobox song | name = Dead Presidents | cover = Jay-ZDeadPresidents.jpg | alt = | type = single | artist = [[Jay-Z]] | album = [[Reasonable Doubt (album)|Reasonable Doubt]] | released = February 20, 1996 | format = {{hlist|[[12-inch single]]|[[Cassette single|cassette]]|[[CD single|CD]]|[[Gramophone record|vinyl]]}} | recorded = 1995 | studio = | venue = | genre = [[East Coast hip hop]] | length = | label = {{hlist|[[Roc-A-Fella Records|Roc-A-Fella]]|[[Priority Records|Priority]]}} | writer = {{hlist|[[Jay-Z|Shawn Carter]]|[[Ski (producer)|David Willis]]|[[Lonnie Liston Smith]]|[[Nas|Nasir Jones]]|[[Pete Rock|Peter Phillips]]}} | producer = [[Ski (producer)|Ski]] | prev_title = [[In My Lifetime (song)|In My Lifetime]] | prev_year = 1994 | next_title = [[Ain't No Nigga]] | next_year = 1996 }}
"'''Dead Presidents'''" is a 1996 song by [[rapping|rapper]] [[Jay-Z]]. It was released as the first promotional single for Jay-Z's debut album ''[[Reasonable Doubt (album)|Reasonable Doubt]]'', although it did not directly appear on the album: a different version, with the same backing track and chorus but different lyrics, called '''"Dead Presidents II"''', appeared on ''Reasonable Doubt'' instead. The single was a commercial success, and was certified as an [[Recording Industry Association of America|RIAA]] [[RIAA certification|certification]] gold single in June 1996. Both versions of the song are regarded as some of the greatest hip-hop songs ever recorded, and "Dead Presidents II" was voted #16 in [[About.com]]'s Top 100 Rap Songs.<ref>[http://rap.about.com/od/top10songs/ss/Top100RapSongs_9.htm Top 100 Rap Songs]</ref>
"Dead Presidents II" also appears in the 2013 video game [[Grand Theft Auto V]] and [[Grand Theft Auto Online]], as part of the Doomsday Heist update, in the blonded Los Santos 97.8 FM radio station.
The title is slang for money because portraits of dead United States presidents appear on most [[Federal Reserve Note]]s.<ref>[http://www.songfacts.com/detail.php?id=7106 Dead Presidents Songfacts]</ref>
The song was produced by [[Ski (producer)|Ski]]. The song [[sampling (music)|samples]] [[Lonnie Liston Smith]]'s "A Garden of Peace" for the track's melody and [[A Tribe Called Quest]]'s "[[Oh My God (A Tribe Called Quest song)|Oh My God (remix)]]" for its percussion; the chorus is a sample of [[Nas]] rapping "I'm out for dead presidents to represent me", from his 1994 song "[[The World Is Yours (Nas song)|The World Is Yours]] ([[Q-Tip (rapper)|Tip]] Mix)".
==Feud with Nas== [[Nas]] was originally invited to re-rap the chorus for Jay-Z and appear in the track's music video, but he declined. Some view these two actions as the foundation of Jay-Z vs. Nas feud.<ref>[http://escobartheory.blogspot.com/2006_06_01_escobartheory_archive.html Escobartheory.]</ref>
When Nas and Jay-Z feuded directly, both rappers discussed the merit of the sampling in the song in individual "diss" records. In Nas' track "Stillmatic Freestyle," he says: {{quote|You show off, I count dough off when you sample my voice.}}
Jay-Z responds to Nas' claims in his song "[[Takeover (song)|Takeover]]" with the lines: {{quote|So yeah, I sampled your voice; you was usin' it wrong: you made it a hot line, I made it a hot song. And you ain't get a coin nigga you was gettin' fucked then; I know who I paid God, [[MC Serch|Serchlite Publishing]].}}
The line was later used in [[Cassidy (rapper)|Cassidy]]'s 2005 hit "[[I'm a Hustla]]": {{quote|Yeah I used dude's voice props to the boy Shawn, He made it a hot line, I made it a hot song.}}
In 2005 at Jay-Z's ''I Declare War'' concert, he performed "Dead Presidents II" with Nas, officially ending their feud.
==Production== In a [[YouTube]] video named ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=RY8EIoMelFc Ski Beatz - the making of Jay-Z's Dead Presidents]''<ref>[http://www.hhnlive.com/features/more/188 "Roc-A-Biz: Ski Beatz"] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070111000000/http://www.hhnlive.com/features/more/188 |date=January 11, 2007 }}. HNNLive.com. January 7, 2007. Retrieved June 23, 2007.</ref> [[Ski Beatz|Ski]] explains how he filtered out the high frequency content of the melody sample (using a lowpass filter) to achieve a more prominent bass line without replaying one in. Ski's ''Beats, Rhymes & Samples'' mixtape contains the Q-Tip remix in the context of a "Dead Presidents" sample, because the original "The World is Yours" had altered lyrics in connection to the sampled vocals. At the end of the sample from the chorus, you can hear the "Whose" from "Whose world is this?" from the beginning of the chorus of "The World is Yours".
==Dead Presidents 3== Jay-Z recorded a track called "Dead Presidents 3" around the time of ''[[The Black Album (Jay-Z album)|The Black Album]]'' but it was never completed. The unfinished song was leaked onto the internet in the fall of 2007, around the release of ''[[American Gangster (album)|American Gangster]]''. In it, Jay-Z referenced some of his lyrics from the original "Dead Presidents" and he used the sample but the sample was played in reverse and had a darker more atmospheric feel to it.
In July 2013 during a rare [[Twitter]] Q&A, a fan asked Jay-Z if "Dead Presidents 3" would be released which then resulted in Jay giving [[Young Guru]] and [[Just Blaze]] the permission to release the track on Young Guru's [[SoundCloud]] account.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jay-Z – DP3|url=http://www.indieshuffle.com/jay-z-dp3/|publisher=Indie Shuffle|accessdate=8 July 2013}}</ref>
==Remixes== Many artists have released remixed versions of Dead Presidents with original lyrics (often freestyles) performed over the original sample and chorus. Notable artists to release versions of Dead Presidents include [[Charles Hamilton (rapper)|Charles Hamilton]], [[Lil B]], [[Lil' Wayne]], [[Drake (entertainer)|Drake]], [[Slug of Atmosphere]], [[Chamillionaire]], [[J. Cole]], Logic, [[Kendrick Lamar]], [[Pusha T]], [[Akala (rapper)|Akala]], [[Lupe Fiasco]], [[Kano (rapper)|Kano]], [[Logic (rapper)|Logic]], [[Slaughterhouse]], [[AZ (rapper)|AZ]], [[Curren$y]] featuring and [[DJ Premier]] who recorded a version with reworked instrumentals with [[Jay-Z]]'s original lyrics and vocals from [[Nas]]' [[The World Is Yours (Nas song)|The World is Yours]] (Remix).
