{{Infobox Musical | name = Sweet and Low | subtitle = | image = SweetAndLowPoster.jpg | image_size = 200px | caption = | music = Various | lyrics = Various | book = David Freedman | basis = | productions = 1930 [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] <!-- Please do not include production-specific (acting, directing, etc.) awards --> | awards = }}
'''''Sweet and Low''''' is a [[Musical theatre|musical]] [[revue]] produced by [[Billy Rose]] and starring [[James Barton (vaudevillian)|James Barton]], [[Fanny Brice]], [[George Jessel (actor)|George Jessel]], and [[Arthur Treacher]]. It features sketches by David Freedman and songs by various composers and lyricists.
The 1930 [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] production was directed by Alexander Leftwich and choreographed by [[Danny Dare]], with additional dances staged by [[Busby Berkeley]]. Scenic design was by [[Jo Mielziner]]. It ran for a week at the Majestic Theatre in [[Brooklyn]] before opening on November 17, 1930 at [[Richard Rodgers Theatre|Chanin's 46th Street Theatre]], where it ran for 184 performances. Although it rarely sold out, Rose transferred it to the [[44th Street Theatre]], where it was more successful at the box office.<ref>Garner, Paul and Mrotek Kissane, Sharon F., ''Mousie Garner: Autobiography of a Vaudeville Stooge''. Jefferson, North Carolina: McFarland & Company 1999. {{ISBN|0-7864-0581-3}}, p. 34</ref>
